00:05:32.030 --> 00:05:35.330
of different texts and
different Mayan languages

00:05:35.330 --> 00:05:36.800
from highland Guatemala.

00:05:36.800 --> 00:05:41.900
I would like to give you a little
bit of background information.

00:05:41.900 --> 00:05:47.590
Highland Guatemala is the
world's second region,

00:05:47.590 --> 00:05:50.750
or the second major region, that
was conquered by the Spanish

00:05:50.750 --> 00:05:54.410
on the American continent in 1554.

00:05:54.410 --> 00:05:58.170
The K'iche' speaking kingdom
of Utatlan was the main power

00:05:58.170 --> 00:05:59.470
in this ethnically

00:05:59.470 --> 00:06:03.740
and linguistically very
diverse Maya highland region

00:06:03.740 --> 00:06:07.560 position:56%
and as John has pointed out already,

00:06:07.560 --> 00:06:10.230
there are many different
Mayan languages

00:06:10.230 --> 00:06:13.050
that are still spoken
today and just in Guatemala

00:06:13.050 --> 00:06:15.610
in this region we have
21 Mayan languages

00:06:15.610 --> 00:06:17.530
that are spoken to this very day.

00:06:17.530 --> 00:06:21.640
So one-third of the Guatemalan
population today speaks a Mayan

00:06:21.640 --> 00:06:26.680
language, something that
is not very well-known.

00:06:26.680 --> 00:06:31.030
From the beginning,
Christian-ization, the mission,

00:06:31.030 --> 00:06:34.250
the conversion to the
Christian faith,

00:06:34.250 --> 00:06:37.060
took place in the indigenous
languages.

00:06:37.060 --> 00:06:41.990
And a particular role was played
by Bartolome de las Casas,

00:06:41.990 --> 00:06:46.080
the so-called "Defender of the
Indians," who ended the bloodshed

00:06:46.080 --> 00:06:48.830
of the conquest, which
was particularly violent

00:06:48.830 --> 00:06:53.180
in highland Guatemala, by
replacing the sword with the gospel

00:06:53.180 --> 00:06:57.760
and successfully pacifying the
resisting providence of Tezoatlan,

00:06:57.760 --> 00:07:03.690
by reaching to the indigenous
population in their own language.

00:07:03.690 --> 00:07:07.980
Guatemala is therefore one of the
best areas to study the encounter

00:07:07.980 --> 00:07:15.390
between pre-Colombian and European
religions and word systems,

00:07:15.390 --> 00:07:20.050 position:56%
because there was so much missionary
documentation and so much material

00:07:20.050 --> 00:07:22.740
that was produced by
these missionaries

00:07:22.740 --> 00:07:25.260
in these indigenous languages.

00:07:25.260 --> 00:07:31.360
And mostly, for the most part,
this material has been neglected

00:07:31.360 --> 00:07:38.610
by researchers and there's
now a small group of people,

00:07:38.610 --> 00:07:42.830
more and more research of
linguist theologians, historians,

00:07:42.830 --> 00:07:45.050
becoming more and more
interested in doing work

00:07:45.050 --> 00:07:51.290
with these missionary text
documents in indigenous languages.

00:07:51.290 --> 00:07:58.360
And the Kislak manuscript 1015
is one of the earliest specimens

00:07:58.360 --> 00:08:02.040
of such missionary or
doctrinic text documents.

00:08:02.040 --> 00:08:05.360
It is, as I already said, a
compilation of various texts

00:08:05.360 --> 00:08:08.360
and different highland
Mayan languages.

00:08:08.360 --> 00:08:12.090
And all of these texts in
this manuscript are copies

00:08:12.090 --> 00:08:16.320
