00:45:23.140 --> 00:45:31.940
Yeah, the missionaries were really
taking a lot of care in thinking

00:45:31.940 --> 00:45:34.800
about which terminology to use.

00:45:34.800 --> 00:45:38.200
And when we compare the
doctrinal literature that we have

00:45:38.200 --> 00:45:41.330
from highland Guatemala, we see
that it's not standardized at all.

00:45:41.330 --> 00:45:43.760
It's very eclectic.

00:45:43.760 --> 00:45:48.170 position:56%
Missionaries from different orders
use different translation techniques

00:45:48.170 --> 00:45:50.140
and different strategies.

00:45:50.140 --> 00:45:54.780
And what we can see is that
there are particular differences

00:45:54.780 --> 00:45:57.920
between Franciscans and Dominicans.

00:45:57.920 --> 00:46:05.270
Franciscans prefer to use
neologisms, so the prime example

00:46:05.270 --> 00:46:09.460
for this is that they
refuse to re-use any kind

00:46:09.460 --> 00:46:13.260 position:56%
of indigenous term for labeling god.

00:46:13.260 --> 00:46:16.490
They would introduce
the Spanish term "dios."

00:46:16.490 --> 00:46:22.860
And maybe change that to the
Mayan sound system a little bit

00:46:22.860 --> 00:46:24.440
so it sounds like "kiosh."

00:46:24.440 --> 00:46:30.680
Yeah, but they would not introduce
any indigenous terminology,

00:46:30.680 --> 00:46:33.600
which is something that
the Dominicans did.

00:46:33.600 --> 00:46:35.240 position:56%
And they did that very deliberately.

00:46:35.240 --> 00:46:41.450
And we can see that also in
documents from other Dominican

00:46:41.450 --> 00:46:46.530
or areas in which the Dominicans
had a lot of missionary activity

00:46:46.530 --> 00:46:49.870
like in Quechua documents
from the Andes.

00:46:49.870 --> 00:46:55.440 position:56%
Anna Dorsen [phonetic] has written
about those in quite a detailed way.

00:46:55.440 --> 00:47:01.080
And yeah, we have very
different approaches here.

00:47:01.080 --> 00:47:05.000 position:56%
The Dominicans, this is what makes
the Dominican materials interesting.

00:47:05.000 --> 00:47:08.520
And this is what makes highland
Guatemala a very interesting place

00:47:08.520 --> 00:47:13.310
for researching the mission and
the production or the creation

00:47:13.310 --> 00:47:17.070
of Christian terminology
and Christian concepts

00:47:17.070 --> 00:47:20.870
in Mayan languages because
we have these two regions,

00:47:20.870 --> 00:47:22.620
we have the K'iche' speaking region

00:47:22.620 --> 00:47:24.730
and we have the Kaqchikel
speaking region,

00:47:24.730 --> 00:47:26.620 position:56%
two languages which are very similar

00:47:26.620 --> 00:47:32.450 position:56%
but the Kaqchikel region was mostly
dominated by Franciscan missionaries

00:47:32.450 --> 00:47:34.930
and the K'iche' region
by Dominicans.

00:47:34.930 --> 00:47:37.870
And they have very different
approaches to translation.

00:47:37.870 --> 00:47:41.800
And you see in the Dominican
material all this re-use

00:47:41.800 --> 00:47:48.480
of terminology and Gary has written
quite extensively about the re-use

00:47:48.480 --> 00:47:50.350
of couplets and parallelism.

00:47:50.350 --> 00:47:58.210
So Domingo de Vico is someone who
has adopted the ritual language

00:47:58.210 --> 00:48:03.170 position:56%
that was used in highland Guatemala,
and is used to the present day,

00:48:03.170 --> 00:48:08.790
Mayan ceremonial specialists
use a specific form

00:48:08.790 --> 00:48:14.210
of ceremonial discourse which
has a lot of parallelisms

00:48:14.210 --> 00:48:19.260
and couplet structure and this
very couplet structure you find

00:48:19.260 --> 00:48:22.070
in these Dominican documents.

00:48:22.070 --> 00:48:28.680
And as I have to reference this
to Gary, I mean this is his work.

00:48:28.680 --> 00:48:30.510
Just [inaudible].

00:48:30.510 --> 00:48:50.350
[ Inaudible ]

00:48:50.350 --> 00:48:52.980
I don't believe so.

00:48:52.980 --> 00:48:55.750
I think, I don't where this is,

00:48:55.750 --> 00:48:57.580
I must honestly say
I must blank on this.

00:48:57.580 --> 00:49:01.970 position:56%
I don't know whether this was a
strategy that missionaries had tried

00:49:01.970 --> 00:49:04.570
in other parts of the world before.

00:49:04.570 --> 00:49:09.550
But it was certainly very
successful and had a good effect

00:49:09.550 --> 00:49:14.030
because Remesal writes
in much detail,

00:49:14.030 --> 00:49:20.070
I mean I've given you a very short
account of this very detailed

00:49:20.070 --> 00:49:22.430
and colorful description
that he has,

00:49:22.430 --> 00:49:29.350
about how the people really loved
these songs and loved this music

00:49:29.350 --> 00:49:34.780
and the harmonies and wanted
to learn how to sing those.

00:49:34.780 --> 00:49:37.980
And they love the outfit
of the Dominican friars

00:49:37.980 --> 00:49:41.010
with their shaved heads
and their black

00:49:41.010 --> 00:49:44.680
and white gowns, which
were interesting.

00:49:44.680 --> 00:49:48.950
It was just exotic, it
was something interesting.

00:49:48.950 --> 00:49:53.430
And that probably did have the
mission, if you were confronted

00:49:53.430 --> 00:49:56.270
with something that
you find exciting,

00:49:56.270 --> 00:49:59.050
you're probably also interested
in learning more about it

00:49:59.050 --> 00:50:02.000
so I think it was a very
successful strategy.

00:50:02.000 --> 00:50:07.510
Wherever it came from, I don't know
whether it has been applied before.

00:50:07.510 --> 00:50:50.520
[ Inaudible ]

00:50:50.520 --> 00:50:54.530 position:56%
I think this text was solely
compiled for the missionary himself.

00:50:54.530 --> 00:50:58.540
We have originally called
him the highland Maya priest,

00:50:58.540 --> 00:51:00.510
but we don't do this anymore

00:51:00.510 --> 00:51:03.370 position:56%
because we don't really know whether
it was really used by a priest

00:51:03.370 --> 00:51:06.280
or by a missionary
of some other order.

00:51:06.280 --> 00:51:09.290
But it was certainly something
that somebody, I mean,

00:51:09.290 --> 00:51:12.440
because we have several texts,
eclectic different texts,

00:51:12.440 --> 00:51:14.560
that were copied by the same hand.

00:51:14.560 --> 00:51:18.240
So there was somebody in the
convent who probably sat down

00:51:18.240 --> 00:51:24.920
and either copied this for himself
or had it copied for someone

00:51:24.920 --> 00:51:29.620
to be used in the field,
to be used on his mission.

00:51:29.620 --> 00:51:35.100
He probably carried this book
with him and these songs were,

00:51:35.100 --> 00:51:38.770
likely these songs, these
original songs that were drafted,

00:51:38.770 --> 00:51:42.660
and they had been sung, they had
been sung all over the highlands.

00:51:42.660 --> 00:51:46.020
They were a part of the
general-- oh, I'm sorry--

00:51:46.020 --> 00:51:51.080
of the general law that
was produced in order

00:51:51.080 --> 00:51:56.820 position:56%
to missionize and preach the gospel.

00:51:56.820 --> 00:52:01.450
And every missionary who came into
highland Guatemala probably wanted

00:52:01.450 --> 00:52:04.550
to know these songs and
thereby wanted a copy of it.

00:52:04.550 --> 00:52:08.240
So this copy was probably
primarily for the missionary

00:52:08.240 --> 00:52:10.150
so that he would have
this in writing,

00:52:10.150 --> 00:52:14.230
since also all the
missionaries who came from Spain,

00:52:14.230 --> 00:52:16.590
they had to learn the languages.

00:52:16.590 --> 00:52:20.430
They came, they knew Spanish
and they obviously knew Latin

00:52:20.430 --> 00:52:26.030
and maybe Greek, but they did not
know the highland Mayan languages.

00:52:26.030 --> 00:52:29.910
So they came and they first learned
the languages and these handbooks

00:52:29.910 --> 00:52:38.120 position:56%
with all this material helped them
to learn and to memorize these songs

00:52:38.120 --> 00:52:43.510
and sing them to the people
who could then repeat them.

00:52:43.510 --> 00:53:00.780
[ Inaudible ]

00:53:00.780 --> 00:53:06.170
Yeah, the region of
Tezoutlan was really fierce.

00:53:06.170 --> 00:53:10.830
The people there really resisted
the conquest and the Spanish

00:53:10.830 --> 00:53:15.650
and it took several attempts
to defeat this region

00:53:15.650 --> 00:53:18.290
and always never succeeded.

00:53:18.290 --> 00:53:24.080
But the conquests in the rest of
the regions had been so bloody,

00:53:24.080 --> 00:53:27.490
that there was, in particular
from Bartolome de las Casas

00:53:27.490 --> 00:53:31.570
and other missionaries, a
lot of resistance to this.

00:53:31.570 --> 00:53:40.590
And I think the choice to use
merchants was a pragmatic one.

00:53:40.590 --> 00:53:44.380
Because these were the only
people who could get in there.

00:53:44.380 --> 00:53:49.390 position:56%
I guess that the people in Tezoutlan
were so defensive the only people

00:53:49.390 --> 00:53:54.120
who they would let in were
probably the merchants who came

00:53:54.120 --> 00:54:00.570
from other provinces and knew the
languages and brought in products

00:54:00.570 --> 00:54:03.050
from other highland Mayan areas

00:54:03.050 --> 00:54:10.510
that were not necessarily
controlled by the Spanish.

